    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nArchive support in Neovim is currently tied to legacy runtime plugins (`zipPlugin.vim` and `tarPlugin.vim`) which:\n\n- mix multiple concerns:\n    - external tool invocations (`zip`, `unzip`, `tar`)\n    - buffer integration (`BufReadCmd`, `BufWriteCmd`)\n    - browsing UI\n- their inputs are file-path oriented and do not treat buffers as first-class inputs\n- are not resuable from Lua\n- make it difficult to integrate with newer modules (e.g `vim.net`)\n- current API requires us to materialize inputs on disk even if they are temprary files (see #38744)\n\n\nThis is very similar to the problems discussed in #32280. We have tighly coupled functionality that blocks us from incremental improvements and add friction for reusability.\n\n\n### Proposed Solution\nWe could introduce a minimal resuable archive Lua API and decouple it from UI concerns:\n\n#### Phase 1: Core API (`vim.archive`)\n```\nvim.archive.list(source, opts?, cb)\nvim.archive.list(source, opts?, cb)\nvim.archive.write(source, member, data, opts?, cb)\n```\nWith the intention of:\n- supporting `{ type = \"file\" }` and `{ type = \"buffer\" }`\n- using async callbacks, that way we decouple UI from the plugins.\n- separating internally format-specific backends for zip and tar (`vim.archive.zip` and `vim.archive.tar` routed by a general `vim.archive` module)\n\n#### Phase 2: Integration\nWe handle as a thin layer on top of the API\n- BufReadCmd `*.zip` and `*.tar.*`\n- Open an archive -> list entries\n- Open an entry -> read into Buffer\n- Write a buffer -> update archive\n\nWe keep it minimal so later is easy to integrate with `vim.ui.tree` (#33914) where `list()` can return data for the tree rendering.\n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
